4. Provide real-time feedback during password entry using JavaScript validation

5. For existing admin accounts, enforce password change on first login

6. Implement password hashing using bcrypt or Argon2 with salt - never store plaintext passwords

7. Implement password history to prevent reuse of recent passwords

8. Consider implementing multi-factor authentication (MFA) as additional protection for admin accounts

Example PHP validation code:
```php
function validatePassword($password) {
    $minLength = 12;
    $errors = array();

    if (strlen($password) < $minLength) {
        $errors[] = "Password must be at least $minLength characters";
    }
    if (!preg_match('/[A-Z]/', $password)) {
        $errors[] = "Password must contain uppercase letters";
    }
    if (!preg_match('/[a-z]/', $password)) {
        $errors[] = "Password must contain lowercase letters";
    }
    if (!preg_match('/\d/', $password)) {
        $errors[] = "Password must contain numbers";
    }
    if (!preg_match('/[@$!%*?&]/', $password)) {
        $errors[] = "Password must contain special characters (@$!%*?&)";
    }

    return $errors;
}

$validationErrors = validatePassword($_POST['password']);
if (!empty($validationErrors)) {
    die(json_encode(['error' => implode(', ', $validationErrors)]));
}
```
